<section>

  <h2 id="if-you-already-know-this-stuff">If You Already Know This Stuff</h2>

  <p>For example&#8230;</p>

  <ul>
    <li class="fragment">if <strong>you do this professionally</strong> (seriously, I&#39;ve had people who get paid to do this take this class???  &#129300;)</li>
    <li class="fragment">or&#8230; if <strong>you&#39;ve already taken several web minor courses</strong>, including web programming and databases</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fragment"><br /> 
<strong>What are you doing here? GET OUT!</strong> &#128073;</p>

  <ul>
    <li class="fragment">Really, though, you probably won&#39;t get much out of the class</li>
    <li class="fragment">And you&#39;ll slack off a bit</li>
    <li class="fragment"><small style="display:inline">(and then get like a B+, and then you&#39;ll try to argue with me about your grade, and I&#39;ll be like <em>I told you not to take this class</em>, and then we&#39;ll both be sad. The end.)</small></li>
  </ul>

</section>

<section>
  <h2 id="more-about-you">More About You&#8230;</h2>

  <h3 id="additionally-i-expect-that-you-would">Additionally, I expect that you would:</h3>

  <ol>
    <li class="fragment">be very <strong>comfortable</strong> using the <strong>commandline</strong></li>
    <li class="fragment">have the ability to install tools, software, etc. &#8230; and troubleshoot installations (<strong>basically <em>know how to use a computer</em> </strong>)</li>
    <li class="fragment">be able <strong>navigate</strong> through your <strong>file system</strong> (both through a file explorer like Finder and through the commandline)</li>
    <li class="fragment">have basic/rudimentary knowledge of <strong>HTML</strong> and <strong>CSS</strong> (even a <a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=90%27s+website&amp;espv=2&amp;tbm=isch&amp;tbo=u&amp;source=univ&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=wegEVMjPJcPxgwTA5YDICg&amp;ved=0CCgQsAQ&amp;biw=1307&amp;bih=729">late 90&#39;s notion</a> of how this stuff works <em>may be</em> fine)</li>
    <li class="fragment"><strong><em>actually do homework and - you know - occasionally come to class</em></strong></li>
    <li class="fragment">low bar, I know&#8230; but I mean it</li>
  </ol>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 id="workload">Workload</h2>

  <p><strong>Some salient quotes from evaluations/reviews</strong> &#8594;</p>

  <ul>
    <li class="fragment">&quot;<strong>Gives Lots of homework</strong> and focuses on too many details at exam. He has some sort of weird smartness that he would like to show off.&quot;</li>
    <li class="fragment">&quot;Great professor. Gives <strong>a decent amount of homework</strong>, but it&#39;s very effective at helping you learn the material.&quot;</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fragment"><br />
So, regardless of whether or not the review was positive or negative, <strong>the common thread is there&#39;s kind of <em>a lot of work</em> involved in this course</strong> &#8230;</p>

  <p class="fragment"><strong>Expect the workload to be on the same level as some your earlier cs courses</strong> (like Intro to CS, Data Structures) &#8594;</p>

</section>
<section>
  <h2 id="workload-continued">Workload Continued</h2>

  <p><strong>Uh, so&#8230; how much work is this <em>really</em>?</strong> &#8594;</p>

  <ul>
    <li class="fragment">almost <strong>weekly homework</strong> (8 total, which is actually less than the number of homeworks for 0002 or 0101) <strong>and a final project</strong></li>
    <li class="fragment">this course is not challenging in the way that something like <em>algorithms</em> is, but it&#39;s challenging because of:
      <ul>
        <li class="fragment">the <strong>wide range of topics</strong> covered</li>
        <li class="fragment">the <strong>volume of hands-on work</strong> (again, though, no more than weekly assignments in 101)</li>
        <li class="fragment">the  <strong>difficult nature of debugging</strong> web applications that involve integrating several technologies</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
    <li class="fragment">a lot of homework will be:
      <ul>
        <li>write your own library that <em>does x</em></li>
        <li>use that library to implement some sort of web application</li>
        <li>use an existing library that already <em>does x</em> to re-write above ^</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 id="too-easydifficult-too-much-work">Too Easy/Difficult, Too Much Work?</h2>

  <p><strong>Consider choosing a different course if you:</strong></p>

  <ol>
    <li class="fragment"><em>are a <strong>professional</strong> web developer</em> or <strong>already know this stuff</strong></li>
    <li class="fragment">think this may be <strong>more work than you accommodate</strong> this semester</li>
    <li class="fragment"><strong>not comfortable with the requirements</strong> (commandline, basic html, css, etc.)</li>
    <li class="fragment">you&#39;re a senior and want an easy C to meet your cs major requirements</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="fragment"><br />
<strong>If you want a slower pace and are <em>truly</em> interested in the material, there are some non major courses around as well</strong></p>

  <ul class="fragment">
    <li><strong>CSCI-UA.60</strong> Database Design &amp; Web Implementation</li>
    <li><strong>CSCI-UA.61</strong> Web Development &amp; Programming</li>
  </ul>

</section>

<section>
  <h2 id="how-to-make-no-one-happy">How to Make No One Happy</h2>

  <p>Students coming into the course <strong>have very different backgrounds when it comes to web development</strong> (from <em>What&#39;s a CSS?</em> to <em>You mean this course doesn&#39;t go into using Redux?</em>) &#8594;</p>

  <ul>
    <li class="fragment">Sooo&#8230; I try to hit the <strong>middle ground</strong></li>
    <li class="fragment">which means, for students with no web development experience, it&#39;s a: &quot;<strong>Hard class for me (no previous exp to webdev) but is fair. There should be a prereq to this class not to let people like me take the class.</strong>&quot;</li>
    <li class="fragment">and for students with web development experience: &quot;<strong>General pace was good - could have maybe been a little faster.</strong>&quot;</li>
    <li class="fragment">just can&#39;t make anyone happy  &#128580; &#8230; though one comment was <strong>(a drawing of a cat)</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fragment"><br />
(this should probably be two courses, and maybe it will eventually be that&#8230;)</p>

</section>

<section>
  <h2 id="that-sounds-pretty-harshboring">That Sounds Pretty Harsh/Boring</h2>

  <p><strong>If you&#39;re concerned about the workload and the material&#8230;</strong> &#8594;</p>

  <ul>
    <li class="fragment">I&#39;m <strong>always available to help</strong>, especially on piazza, but also before and after class, during office hours and by appointment</li>
    <li class="fragment">We&#39;ll also have a tutor (I&#39;ll post a schedule mid-week)</li>
  </ul>

  <p><br />
<strong>If you think it&#39;s going too slowly&#8230;</strong> &#8594;</p>

  <ul>
    <li class="fragment">challenge yourself&#8230; for example, if the assignment is to make a simple game</li>
    <li class="fragment"><strong>make your own library/framework</strong> from scratch (for example, if you use rxjs or immutable.js, try to re-implement parts of it), and use it to write the game</li>
    <li class="fragment">or&#8230; <strong>add features</strong> to make the game <em>more complete</em> - like&#8230; adding an undo move feature</li>
    <li class="fragment">or&#8230; add support tooling like unit tests, linters, and other build tools</li>
    <li class="fragment">or&#8230; or <em>actually</em> deploy it</li>
  </ul>

</section>

